Reflections: 

What Surprised Me
•	How strong discovery bias dominates physics
•	How few features explain most signal
•	Transit vs RV are fundamentally different populations


What Failed
•	Stellar metallicity had weak predictive power
•	Very long-period planets confused all models
•	Distance alone is not enough without brightness


Surprises & Key Observations
•	Systematic missingness dominates:
o	As expected, RV-detected planets often lack radius measurements, and Transit-detected planets often lack mass. This confirmed that missingness is method-dependent, not random.
•	Right-skewed distributions:
o	Both orbital period and planet mass are extremely right-skewed, as anticipated from observational biases (small, low-mass planets are harder to detect). Log transforms were essential for modeling.
•	Physical relationships were captured by the model:
o	SHAP feature importance aligned with expectations:
	rv_signal_proxy and mass_ratio were strong positive contributors.
	Longer orbital periods (log_orbper) had negative SHAP contributions, reflecting survey limitations.
•	Distance-adjusted brightness mattered:
o	As expected, more distant systems are less likely to have RV measurements due to SNR limits.


What Worked Well
•	Pipeline rigor:
o	Using a ColumnTransformer with imputation + robust scaling and limited one-hot encoding allowed for zero-leakage preprocessing.
•	Feature engineering encoded physics:
o	Mass ratio, RV proxy, and log-scaled periods captured astrophysical detectability in a way simple statistical features could not.
•	Stratified splitting prevented leakage:
o	By stratifying on planet_id, no planet appears in multiple splits, ensuring realistic evaluation.
•	Explainability:
o	SHAP validated that the model’s decisions make physical sense, increasing trust for astronomers.


Challenges & Lessons Learned
•	Imbalanced classes:
o	RV planets are less frequent than Transit planets, so careful stratification and evaluation metrics (ROC-AUC, PR-AUC) were essential.
•	Extreme values & outliers:
o	Some orbital periods exceeded 10,000 days or had negative values; capping and cleaning were necessary to prevent model distortion.
•	Sensitivity to missing features:
o	Dropping pl_bmassj reduced performance gracefully, showing the model is robust but highlights dependence on key physical measurements.
•	Survey bias is unavoidable:
o	Model performance varies with discovery era, reflecting that older surveys had limited sensitivity.


What Could Be Improved / Future Work
•	Instrument-aware modeling:
o	Incorporate instrument characteristics to explicitly model detection biases.
•	Hierarchical modeling:
o	Treat stars as random effects to better handle multiple planets per system.
•	Uncertainty quantification:
o	Integrate predictive uncertainties (e.g., conformal prediction) for telescope time optimization.
•	Additional physics-based features:
o	Include eccentricity, stellar metallicity, and incident flux in more sophisticated combinations.
•	Temporal generalization:
o	Test model robustness on future survey data (e.g., TESS, PLATO).


Takeaways for Astronomers & ML Practitioners
•	ML can optimize follow-up strategies, not discover planets directly.
•	Carefully engineered features grounded in physics outperform naive models.
•	Systematic biases in the dataset (method, distance, stellar type) are as important as algorithm choice.
•	Explainable AI (SHAP) provides a bridge between model predictions and physical intuition, making the results credible for telescope scheduling decisions.


Summary:
This project demonstrates that careful feature engineering, bias-aware splitting, and robust pipelines can produce interpretable ML models that respect astrophysical constraints and meaningfully support exoplanet follow-up prioritization.
